03515nam a2200445 a 6808732UtOrBLW20150213154312.0m     o  d        cr un|||||||||150213s2015    enk     o     000 0 eng d  a9781784410636 (electronic bk.)  aocn903410561  aexclude  aUtOrBLWdAEU 4aLB14.7b.C37 2015 7aJNF2bicssc 7aJN2bicssc 7aEDU0110002bisacsh 7aEDU0000002bisacsh  a37.0104a370.1223  aInternet AccessbAEU00aCase study evaluationh[electronic resource] :bpast, present and future challenges /cedited by Jill Russell, Trisha Greenhalgh, Saville Kushner.  aBingley, U.K. :bEmerald,c2015.  a1 online resource (xv, 251 p.)1 aAdvances in program evaluation,x1474-7863 ;vv. 150 aCase study, methodology and educational evaluation: a personal view / Clement Adelman -- Letters from a headmaster / Barry MacDonald -- Storytelling and educational understanding / Terry Denny -- Case study as antidote to the literal / Saville Kushner -- Thinking about case studies in 3-D : researching the NHS clinical commissioning landscape in England / Julia Segar, Kath Checkland, Anna Coleman, Imelda McDermott -- The case for evaluating process and worth : evaluation of a programme for carers and people with dementia / Samantha Abbato -- The collapse of "primary care" in medical education : a case study of Michigan's community/university health partnerships project / Brian McKenna -- 'Lead' standard evaluation / David Jenkins -- Freedom from the rubric / Robert Stake -- Twice-told tales? How public inquiry could inform n of 1 case study research / Trisha Greenhalgh -- Evaluation as the co-construction of knowledge : case studies of place-based leadership and public sector innovation / Jo Howard, Arturo Flores, Robin Hambleton -- Evaluation noir : the other side of the experience / Acacia Cochise, Saville Kushner.  aAccess restricted to authorized users and institutions.  aIn todays world, with its preoccupation with impact assessments and results-based management, program evaluation is all too often framed as an affirmation of an official narrative rather than as a source of alternatives.  The power of case study is its insistence on opening up rather than suppressing the complexity of social programs, on documenting multiple voices and exploring contested viewpoints.  In this way, case study resists the trend towards evaluations that simply focus on what works, that reduce the complexity of social life to a single narrative, and to formulations that strip out most of what matters.  Now more than ever, as government policies and programs orientate to global economic crisis and its impact on the lives of citizens and communities, we require evaluations that resist information loss and produce richness.  a44 0aEducationxEvaluation.1 aRussell, Jill.1 aGreenhalgh, Trisha.1 aKushner, Saville. 0aAdvances in program evaluation ;vv. 15.403University of Alberta Accessuhttp://www.emeraldinsight.com/1474-7863/15z(Unlimited Concurrent Users)  hUAINzEBS  aInternet AccesswLCc1i6808732-1001lINTERNETmUAINTERNETrYsYtE-RESOURCEu2/23/2015xE-BOOKzEBS01bhttp://viaf.org/viaf/62764542